{"author":{"id":"458c2786e2fb21c7f2463be283bdb1d457c6c22ed9854985782318ab918e2e3f"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1438093554,"nonce":"PTRZ54x+bFdQU9syc+XMoAksquM=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDEyNTYyNjU4MA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/104#issuecomment-125626580"},"message":"The $ENV vars seems to be fixed. However, when package_htseq_0_6 requires numpy, the LD_LIBRARY_PATH is never set, which means that during execution, numpy is unable to find the atlas library.\n\nI could think of a few of ways to fix this. The first suggested by @gregvonkuster involves exporting an environment var from ATLAS and using that for any package that requires numpy. While this would work, it seems very tedious for the tool writers. It has the benefit, however, of not requiring any changes to Galaxy and thus could be implemented quickly.\n\nAnother option would be to source each env.sh file for any required dependencies. To me, as a tool developer, this is what I would have expected Galaxy to do. If I say I require numpy, I get a working numpy with no further effort.\n\nFinally, (and this could be done in conjunction with the above options), would be to use configure flags to specify library and include paths during installations so that LD_LIBRARY_PATH does not need to be set. For example: \n\n```\nCFLAGS=\"-I$HOME/include\" CPPFLAGS=\"-I$HOME/include\" LDFLAGS=\"-L$HOME/lib -Wl,-rpath,$HOME/lib\" ./configure --prefix=$HOME\n```\n\nThe downside here is that if a dependency gets changed (and moved somehow, etc) the downstream packages would need to be rebuilt. I'm in favor of sourcing the env.sh for each dependency. Thoughts?","files":null}]}